0 DYING~
When your character dies, you are reincarnated back at the Altar of the Temple
of Devota.  Your corpse is left behind in the room where you were killed,
together with all of your equipment.  Your gold stays with you, however.
The act of retrieving your equipment is referred to as a corpse retrieval and
is commonly abbreviated as CR.

Any spells which were affecting you are canceled by death.

Following and groups are not affected by death.

You lose experience points for dying.  The amount you lose is half-way back to
the beginning of your level.  Thus, if you have a bad day and die several
times, the penalties won't clobber you.

Corpses decay after time. For mobiles, the objects inside corpses decay with
the corpse.  If a player's corpse decays, his or her equipment will remain
on the ground where he died.  Player corpses last *roughly* 30 hours of
game time (i.e. 30 ticks; see help TICK for more info on how this corresponds
to real time.)

Normally, only the player who died, or someone in the same group, can
retrieve objects from a player's corpse.  However, the noloot flag may be
turned off to allow others to retrieve items from your corpse; read help
NOLOOT for more information.  In addition, the corpses of those who have a
KILLER, THIEF or TRAITOR flag may be looted by anyone.
~

0 EXPERIENCE LEVEL XP~
Your character advances in power by gaining experience.  The number of
experience points you need to advance a level is determined by your race
and class.


You gain experience by:

    being part of a group that kills a monster

You lose experience by:

    fleeing from combat
    recalling out of combat
    being the target of certain spells
    dying

The experience you get from a kill depends on several things: how many players
are in your group; your level versus the level of the monster; your alignment
versus the monster's alignment; how many of this monster have been killed
lately; your age in hours; and some random variation.
~

-1 GUILDS~
The guild system on ToC is designed to allow players to gain knowledge in
a class other than the one they started with or to become specialized in
their chosen profession.  This creates something that is close to a
multi-class character.  In order to pick up another class you will have to
make some sacrifices in what you can learn.  For example, those whose
primary class is other than mage cannot learn some of the higher level
magical spells.  You can only join one guild in a lifetime and you cannot
'un-guild' once you join.  When you join a guild, you will have access to
that guild's meeting place, which is protected by a powerful guard whose
sole job is keeping those who are not members from entering.

To join a guild, look for Melancholy in the oak tree as he has the
necessary paperwork to register your membership in the guild of your choice.
Read help JOIN for more information on joining a guild.  NOTE THAT IF
YOU DO NOT JOIN A GUILD BY LEVEL 6, YOU WILL AUTOMATICALLY BE ENROLLED
IN THE GUILD THAT CORRESPONDS TO YOUR CLASS AND WILL NOT AUTOMATICALLY
GAIN THE DEFAULT GUILD SKILLS.  That is, you will have to spend trains to
gain your guild default.  In addition, monks and necromancers are not
permitted to multiclass and are, therefore, automatically enrolled in their
corresponding guilds when they begin.

If you multiclass it may raise the amount of experience you need per level,
depending on your race.  The additional experience needed is:

	 mageguild   clericguild    thiefguild    warriorguild

dwarf     200           150             125            200

elf       100           125             150            200

human       0             0              0              0

hobbit    200           150             125            150

saurian   200           150             250            200


For more help on the individual guilds see helps on:

UNIVERSITY OF MAGIC (mages' guild)
TEMPLE OF BREAS (clerics' guild)
CITADEL OF WAR (warriors' guild
HOUSE OF THIEVES (thieves' guild)
PALM OF THE CREATOR (monks' guild - not available for multiclass)
MORGUE OF DRESDEN (necromancers' guild - not available for multiclass)

After you have joined a guild, you can type gainlist to show where you
can gain which skill/group. You can then also type teachlist where you
can learn your new skills/spells.

~


0 TICK~
Many of the game actions are based upon interval timers, including combat,
most autonomous monster actions, hp/mana/move regeneration, spell duration,
weather, and area resetting.

Of these timers, the hp/mana/move regeneration timer is popularly called the
'tick'.  Ticks on this mud average 60 seconds of real time, but the actual
amount varies randomly from 40 seconds to 80 seconds.

Area resetting happens roughly every 3 minutes if no one is in the area, less
often (15 minutes) if some one is.  Also note that objects lying on the ground
will not be regenerated if anyone is in the area when it resets.
~

